{"title_page": "Aberdeen, Hong Kong", "text_new": "{{About|Aberdeen, Hong Kong|other uses of Aberdeen|Aberdeen (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use Hong Kong English|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Chinese|title=Aberdeen, Hong Kong|pic=File:Aberdeen Harbour in 2016.jpg|piccap= The view of Aberdeen Harbour from [[Ap Lei Chau Bridge]]|c=\u9999\u6e2f\u4ed4|p=Xi\u0101ngg\u01cengz\u01cei|population=60,000i=h\u0153\u014b<sub>55</sub> k\u0254\u014b<sub>35</sub> ts\u0250\u026a<sub>35</sub>|j=hoeng<sup>1</sup> gong<sup>2</sup> zai<sup>2</sup>|l=Little [[Hong Kong]]|showflag=j}}\n'''Aberdeen''' {{IPAc-en|audio=Aberdeencity.OGG|\u00e6|b|\u0259r|\u02c8|d|i\u02d0|n}} is an area and town on southwest [[Hong Kong Island]] in [[Hong Kong]]. Administratively, it is part of the [[Southern District (Hong Kong)|Southern District]]. While the name \"Aberdeen\" could be taken in a broad sense to encompass the areas of Aberdeen (town), [[Wong Chuk Hang]], [[Ap Lei Chau]], [[Tin Wan]], [[Wah Kwai Estate]] and [[Wah Fu Estate]], it is more often used to refer to the town only. According to the population census conducted in 2011, the total population of the Aberdeen area is approximately 80,000.\n\nAberdeen is famous not only to tourists but also to Hong Kong locals for its [[Aberdeen floating village|floating village]] and floating seafood restaurants located in the Aberdeen Harbour. The [[Tanka (ethnic group)|Tanka people]], who used to live on boats in the Aberdeen Harbour, are generally associated with the fishing industry, and there are still several dozens of them living on boats in the harbour.\n{{TOC limit|2}}\n\n== Etymology ==\nThis town is named in memory of [[George Hamilton-Gordon, 4th Earl of Aberdeen]], former [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] (1852-1855) and former [[Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs]] (1841-1846). The statesman's title was invested to [[Aberdeen]] in Scotland. Hong Kong's \"Aberdeen\" is also the name of a harbour and a housing estate:\n* '''Aberdeen Harbour''' is the harbour between Aberdeen (town) and [[Ap Lei Chau]], and is one of the nine [[List of harbours in Hong Kong|harbours in Hong Kong]]. It is known for its view and is a popular tourist spot. During the fishing moratorium and [[typhoon]] weather, the [[Aberdeen Typhoon Shelters]] have provided a parking spot for [[fishing vessels]] owned by local fishermen.\n* '''Aberdeen Centre''' is a private housing estate located in Aberdeen town, owned by [[Hutchison Whampoa Limited]] company. The twenty buildings (blocks), providing 2,788 private apartments, have provided a home for Hong Kong middle-class families for more than thirty years.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Aberdeen Centre.JPG|thumb|The entrance of the Aberdeen Square in Aberdeen Centre]]\nStarting from the [[Ming Dynasty]], \"Hong Kong\" became the original name for the presently-named Aberdeen village.<ref name=\"Aberdeen Guide\">\"A short guide to Aberdeen\", from a sign at Aberdeen Floating Village, Published by: Southern District Council, Hong Kong. Date visited: 12 October 2009.</ref> In the early 19th century, foreigners who landed near Aberdeen Village mistook the name of the village \"Hong Kong\" for the whole island.  When the foreigners eventually realized their mistake, the name \"Hong Kong\" was already commonly used to refer to the entire island.<ref name=\"Aberdeen Guide\" />\n\nIn Cantonese, Aberdeen is known indigenously as ''Hong Kong Tsai'' which means \"Hong Kong Minor\", \"Son of Hong Kong\" or \"Little Hong Kong\". It is believed that Aberdeen is where the name of Hong Kong (more accurately transcribed as ''Heung Kong'') originates. ''Heung Kong Tsuen'' (\u9999\u6e2f\u6751, \"Hong Kong village\") on Ap Lei Chau was mentioned on [[Ming dynasty|Ming]]-era maps. Another walled village called Heung Kong Wai in Wong Chuk Hang was also founded during the [[Qianlong Emperor|Qianlong]] era of the [[Qing Dynasty]]. ''Hong Kong'' means \"fragrant harbour\", and it was Aberdeen where incense trees (''[[Aquilaria sinensis]]'') from the [[New Territories]] used to be brought for export to other cities in [[China]]. One alternative Chinese name was ''Shek Pai Wan''<ref>[http://irc.aa.tufs.ac.jp/thomson/vol_1/mother/102.html \"Hong Kong\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161027005209/http://irc.aa.tufs.ac.jp/thomson/vol_1/mother/102.html |date=27 October 2016 }}, ''Illustrations of China and Its People'', John Thomson 1837\u20131921, (London, 1873\u20131874)</ref> (\u77f3\u6392\u7063).\n\nIn the [[Second World War]], during the [[Japanese occupation of Hong Kong]] (1941-1945), the Chinese name of Aberdeen, ''Hong Kong Tsai'', was transformed into Japanese as ''Moto Hong Kong'' (\u5143\u9999\u6e2f), meaning \"The Origin of Hong Kong\".\n\n==Authorities==\n[[Image:Aberdeen Municipal Services Building 201508.jpg|right|thumb|Aberdeen Municipal Services Building]]\nThe Aberdeen Kai-Fong Association (abbreviated \"AKA\"; {{zh|t=\u9999\u6e2f\u4ed4\u8857\u574a\u798f\u5229\u6703}}, literally means \"Aberdeen Neighbours Association\"), located at 180B Aberdeen Main Road, provides outreach and elderly services throughout the Southern District. It provides teenager services through the Harmony Life Enrichment Centre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aka.org.hk/hlec/|title=\u5c1a\u8861\u6210\u9577\u53ca\u57f9\u8a13\u4e2d\u5fc3 Harmony Life Enrichment Centre|website=www.aka.org.hk|access-date=18 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140313024251/http://www.aka.org.hk/hlec/|archive-date=13 March 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It also aims to bridge the divide between teenagers and the elderly in the district through the Linkages Centre, located in Carpark Block, Shek Pai Wan Estate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aka.org.hk/index.php|title=Welcome to AKA \u9999\u6e2f\u4ed4\u574a\u6703|website=www.aka.org.hk|access-date=18 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201143757/http://www.aka.org.hk/index.php|archive-date=1 February 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Tung Wah Group of Hospitals]] organisation has a total of four social enterprises in Aberdeen; one of them is Cookeasy,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cookeasy.tungwahcsd.org/aboutus/|title=CookEasy|access-date=20 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017040626/http://cookeasy.tungwahcsd.org/aboutus/|archive-date=17 October 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> which is a project in collaboration with the [[The Hong Kong and China Gas Company|Towngas]] company, creating job opportunities for the disabled and promoting healthy diet culture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tungwah.org.hk/|title=\u6771\u83ef\u4e09\u9662|access-date=20 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130814030037/http://www.tungwah.org.hk/|archive-date=14 August 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAberdeen is one of the 19 constituencies of the [[Southern District Council]]. Each constituency has one elected council member in the [[Southern District Council]]. {{As of|2018}}, the council member representing the area of Aberdeen is Pauline Yam.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.districtcouncils.gov.hk/south/english/members/info/dc_member_list.php|title=Southern District Council - Southern DC Members|website=www.districtcouncils.gov.hk|access-date=3 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180425225045/http://www.districtcouncils.gov.hk/south/english/members/info/dc_member_list.php|archive-date=25 April 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n===Food===\n[[Image:Jumbo Floating Restaurant 1.jpg|left|thumb|Jumbo Floating Restaurant]]\n[[Image:HK Aberdeen \u9999\u6e2f\u4ed4\u820a\u5927\u8857 80 Old Main Street \u5c71\u7abf\u8b1d\u8a18\u9b5a\u86cb Tse Kee Fish Ball Noodle shop sign visitors March-2012.jpg|right|thumb|People queuing up in front of Tse Kee Restaurant]]\n[[Image:Ac4 interior 201508.jpg|right|thumb|Restaurants in Aberdeen Centre]]\n[[Image:BM40615A Lau Kee traditional boat noodles 22-04-2019.jpg|right|thumb|Lau Kee traditional boat noodles]]\nMoored in the harbour between Wong Chuk Hang and [[Ap Lei Chau]], the [[Jumbo Floating Restaurant]] is a popular tourist spot. Designed to resemble a floating palace of imperial China, it has attracted over 30 million visitors since opening in 1976.\n\nThe family-run Shan Loon Tse Kee Fish Balls Restaurant (\u5c71\u7abf\u8b1d\u8a18) served [[Chiuchow cuisine|Chiuchow-style]] [[fish ball]] with soup noodles for 65 years until it closed on 31 March 2012 due to rising fish prices and staffing problems.<ref>Man, Joyce [http://www.cnngo.com/hong-kong/eat/tse-kee-fish-balls-831604 \"Aberdeen's best fish ball shop to close\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229000121/http://www.cnngo.com/hong-kong/eat/tse-kee-fish-balls-831604 |date=29 February 2012 }} ''CNN Go''. 24 February 2012. Retrieved 2012-03-04</ref> The Tse Kee Restaurant served famous guests such as [[Christopher Patten]], former [[Governor of Hong Kong]] (1992-1997); [[Donald Tsang]], former [[Chief Executive of Hong Kong]] (Head of the Government) (2005-2012); [[Henry Tang]], former [[Chief Secretary for Administration of Hong Kong]] (2007-2011); [[Tony Leung Ka-fai|Tony Leung]], a famous actor; [[Chua Lam]], a well-known food critic; and [[Eason Chan]], a celebrated singer. Tse Kee Restaurant helped make \"Aberdeen Fish Balls Noodles Culture\" (\u9999\u6e2f\u4ed4\u9b5a\u86cb\u7c89) well-known.\n\nSix [[Cantonese restaurant|Jau Laus]] (Cantonese restaurants, \u9152\u6a13) such as [[:zh-tw:\u7a3b\u9999\u96c6\u5718|The Tao Heung]] and [[:zh-tw:\u5bcc\u81e8\u96c6\u5718|The Foo Lum]] are located in the neighborhood of Aberdeen. A traditional Cantonese restaurant called Chau Kee (\u5468\u8a18) is located on the Aberdeen Main Road. The noodles restaurants group Nam Kee (\u5357\u8a18) started in Aberdeen in the early 1980s, promoting the \"Aberdeen Fish Balls Noodles Culture\" (\u9999\u6e2f\u4ed4\u9b5a\u86cb\u7c89). The Nam Kee has two restaurants in Aberdeen, along with thirteen others in Hong Kong. There are several other Chinese noodles restaurants located in Aberdeen Centre as well.\n\nFast food restaurants such as [[McDonald's]], [[KFC]], [[Yoshinoya]], [[Fairwood (restaurant)|Fairwood]], [[Caf\u00e9 de Coral (restaurant)|Caf\u00e9 de Coral]] and [[Maxim's Catering|Maxim's MX]] are located in Aberdeen Centre, along with [[Cha Chaan Teng]] (Hong Kong-style fast food restaurants) such as Tai Hing Restaurant (\u592a\u8208) and [[Tsui Wah Restaurant]].\n\nJapanese restaurants such as [[Genki Sushi|Genki]], Watei (\u548c\u4ead) and Sushi Express; Thai One, a Thai restaurant; and Viet's Choice (\u8d8a\u68e7), a Vietnamese restaurant, are also located in Aberdeen Centre. The Pacific Bar is located in Aberdeen Centre as well, serving mainly foreigners living in 'Aberdeen Centre', the private housing estate.\n\n===Festivals and events===\n[[Image:Dragonboat Race in Aberdeen, Hong Kong.jpg|thumb|left|Dragon boat race in Aberdeen Harbour]]\nDuring the [[Tuen Ng Festival]], also known as the Dragon Boat Festival, Aberdeen Harbour becomes the venue of the [[dragon boat]] race in the Southern District. District authorities also hold similar races on Duanwu Festival Day in harbours or rivers of their districts. Although the Aberdeen Harbour race is not as famous as the [[Shing Mun River]] race, it still attracts many tourists and locals every year.\n\nThe Southern District Tourism and Culture Festival,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.travelsouth.hk/en/news/2013|title=Southern District Tourism and Culture Festival 2013|website=www.travelsouth.hk|access-date=20 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203104944/http://www.travelsouth.hk/en/news/2013|archive-date=3 February 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> held by the Southern District Council, organizes races in the Aberdeen Promenade, tours of Aberdeen town, and the Mid-Autumn Fire Dragon Festival in the Aberdeen area every year.\n\nAberdeen Square, located in Aberdeen Centre, is a frequent venue for local organisations' events, including fairs, promotion events and charity events. The square is sometimes used by the [[Southern District Council]] to hold fairs and evening concerts during festivals such as the [[Chinese New Year]] and [[Christmas]].\n\n===Tourism===\n[[File:Aberdeen Sightseeing Sampan Pier 201508.jpg|thumb|right|The view of Sampan Pier near Aberdeen Harbour]]\n[[File:Aberdeen Promenade 201508.jpg|thumb|right|Aberdeen Promenade]]\n\n[[Aberdeen Promenade]], located right next to Aberdeen Harbour on the Aberdeen town side, as well as the [[Ap Lei Chau Bridge]] and [[Aberdeen Channel Bridge]], are famous places for tourists to take photographs of Aberdeen Harbour. The two areas attract many tourists.\n\nThe route of Big Bus Tours Hong Kong<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bigbustours.com/en/hong-kong/hong-kong-bus-tours|title=Hong Kong Bus Tours with Big Bus - Hop-On Discover Hop-Off Explore|website=www.bigbustours.com|access-date=3 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180908215819/https://www.bigbustours.com/en/hong-kong/hong-kong-bus-tours/|archive-date=8 September 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> includes Aberdeen Praya Road, where tourists can take photographs of Aberdeen Harbour on open-top buses.\n\n[[Sampans]] (junks) can be hired by tourists for a tour of Aberdeen Harbour.\n\nAberdeen attracts many tourists as it is in the vicinity of [[Ocean Park Hong Kong|Ocean Park]], also located in the Southern District, near the Aberdeen Sports Ground, which is the other famous theme park apart from [[Hong Kong Disneyland]].\n\n==Infrastructure==\n===Hotels===\nMojo Nomad Aberdeen is located at 100 Shek Pai Wan Road, and has 52 rooms.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mojonomad.com/aberdeen/|title=Aberdeen Harbour Hotel Hong Kong - Co-Living & Co-working|website=Mojo Nomad|access-date=3 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190203071820/https://www.mojonomad.com/aberdeen/|archive-date=3 February 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The L'hotel Island South, at 55 Wong Chuk Hang Road, is located near the popular [[Ocean Park Hong Kong|Ocean Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lhotelgroup.com/en/hotel/lhotel-island-south/Home|title=L'hotel - Family Hotels in Hong Kong - Hong Kong Hotels - L'hotel Island South|website=www.lhotelgroup.com|access-date=3 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181211212652/http://www.lhotelgroup.com/en/hotel/lhotel-island-south/Home|archive-date=11 December 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Hospitals===\n[[Image:HK GranthamHospital.JPG|right|thumb|[[Grantham Hospital]]]]\n[[Grantham Hospital]], located at 125 Wong Chuk Hang Road, has been serving the citizens of the Southern District for more than half a century along with [[Queen Mary Hospital (Hong Kong)|Queen Mary Hospital]] (also located near Aberdeen). Grantham Hospital specializes in comprehensive medical treatment for adult heart and lung diseases, as well as acute geriatrics and palliative medicine services.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ha.org.hk/visitor/ha_visitor_index.asp?Content_ID=100139&Lang=ENG&Dimension=100&Parent_ID=10036&Ver=HTML|title=Grantham Hospital|publisher=Hospital Authority|access-date=18 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201173443/http://www.ha.org.hk/visitor/ha_visitor_index.asp?Content_ID=100139&Lang=ENG&Dimension=100&Parent_ID=10036&Ver=HTML|archive-date=1 February 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n[[File:HK 1 Wong Chuk Hang Road \u9999\u6e2f\u4ed4\u5de5\u696d\u5b78\u6821 Aberdeen Technical School ATS Sir Robert Ho Tung bust April-2012.JPG|thumb|200px]]\n[[Canadian International School of Hong Kong]], Singapore International School and Victoria Shanghai Academy are all located on [[Nam Long Shan]]. Both Canadian International School and Victoria Shanghai Academy are International Baccalaureate World Schools, and run all three educational programs of the IB. The International Montessori School<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ims.edu.hk/|title=Home - The International Montessori School|website=www.ims.edu.hk|access-date=3 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181202023505/https://www.ims.edu.hk/|archive-date=2 December 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> is located on Ap Lei Chau near Aberdeen.\n[[South Island School]] is located nearby on Hong Kong Island.\n\nLocal Chinese high schools in Aberdeen district include Pui Tak Canossian College,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ptcc.edu.hk/|title=\u5609\u8afe\u6492\u57f9\u5fb7\u66f8\u9662|website=www.ptcc.edu.hk|access-date=3 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180626112153/https://www.ptcc.edu.hk/|archive-date=26 June 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> St. Peter's Secondary School in Aberdeen Centre,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stpeter.edu.hk/|title=\u8056\u4f2f\u591a\u797f\u4e2d\u5b78|website=www.stpeter.edu.hk|access-date=3 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181229052958/http://stpeter.edu.hk/|archive-date=29 December 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[:zh:\u9999\u6e2f\u4ed4\u5de5\u696d\u5b78\u6821|Aberdeen Technical School]] in Wong Chuk Hang<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ats.edu.hk/ |title=Aberdeen Technical School |accessdate=2008-04-02 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080331095133/http://www.ats.edu.hk/ |archivedate=2008-03-31 }}</ref> and Aberdeen Baptist Lui Ming Choi College in Ap Lei Chau.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.ablmcc.edu.hk/index/index18.aspx?nnnid=1|title=\u9999\u6e2f\u4ed4\u6d78\u4fe1\u6703\u5442\u660e\u624d\u66f8\u9662|website=web.ablmcc.edu.hk|access-date=3 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190203071820/https://web.ablmcc.edu.hk/index/index18.aspx?nnnid=1|archive-date=3 February 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\n[[File:Aberdeen Promenade Bus Stop.jpg|thumb|\"Aberdeen Promenade, Aberdeen Praya Road\" Bus Stop]]\nTo arrive at Aberdeen or Aberdeen Harbour, travellers can take buses 7, 37A, 37B, 37X, 38, 40P, 41A, 42, 42C, 48, 70, 70A, 71, 71P, 72, 73, 73P, 76, 77, 77X, 78, 91, 91A, 93, 93A, 93C, 94, 94A, 95, 95C, 98, 107, 107P, 170, 973, A10, N72 or N170, and alight at the bus stop \"Aberdeen Promenade, Aberdeen Praya Road\". This bus stop is located directly beside Aberdeen Harbour.\n\nAberdeen is served by [[Pok Fu Lam Road]], [[Aberdeen Tunnel]] and [[Nam Fung Road]] through [[Wong Chuk Hang]]. [[Nam Fung Road]] connects [[Deep Water Bay Road]], which also connects [[Wong Nai Chung Gap Road]] to [[Happy Valley, Hong Kong|Happy Valley]]. A bridge called [[Ap Lei Chau Bridge]] links Aberdeen with [[Ap Lei Chau]] over Aberdeen Harbour.\n\n[[Aberdeen Station (MTR)|Aberdeen Station]], of the proposed [[South Island Line (West)|South Island Line West Section]] of the [[MTR]] will be in Aberdeen. Currently the closest station is [[Wong Chuk Hang Station|Wong Chuk Hang]] on the [[South Island Line]], where feeder bus and minibus routes to Aberdeen are available. \n\nRail passengers may also reach Aberdeen by using [[kai-to]] ferry from [[Ap Lei Chau|Main Street, Ap Lei Chau]] near [[Lei Tung station]] (Exit A1). In addition to the Ap Lei Chau route, regular ferries also depart from Aberdeen to [[Yung Shue Wan]] and [[Sok Kwu Wan]] on [[Lamma Island]], and [[Po Toi Island]].\n\nTransport to and from the boats in the harbour is usually provided by [[sampan]]s. These can also be hired to Lamma Island.\n\n==Recreation==\n===Sports===\n[[Image:Aberdeen Sports Ground viewed from Bennet's Hill.jpg|right|thumb|Aberdeen Sports Ground]]\n[[Aberdeen Sports Ground]] is a major sports and events venue in the [[Southern District (Hong Kong)|Southern District]]. It is usually an annual School Sports Day venue for many local primary and secondary schools in the Southern District.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.lcsd.gov.hk/clpss/en/webApp/Facility/Details.do?ftid=38&did=11 |title=Aberdeen Sports Ground |publisher=Leisure and Cultural Services Department   |df= }}</ref>  It is also the usual venue of the [[Famine events#30 Hour Famine|30-Hour Famine]] held by [[World Vision]] Hong Kong. The Aberdeen Sports Ground is the home ground of the district's football team, [[Southern District RSA]].\n\nThe Aberdeen Sports Centre is located on the 5/F and 6/F of the Aberdeen Municipal Services Building, No. 203 Aberdeen Main Road. The Aberdeen Sports Centre includes a multi-purpose arena, which can be converted into one basketball court or one volleyball court or four badminton courts. There is also a squash court, which can be converted into a table tennis room or a multi-purpose activity room.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lcsd.gov.hk/clpss/en/webApp/Facility/Details.do?ftid=0&did=11 |title=Aberdeen Sports Centre  |publisher=Leisure and Cultural Services Department   |df= }}</ref>\n\nThe Aberdeen Tennis and Squash Centre is located at No. 1 Aberdeen Praya Road, next to the Ocean Court Building. The Aberdeen Tennis and Squash Centre includes 8 tennis courts and six squash courts, which can be converted into table tennis rooms or multi-purpose activity rooms, two American pool rooms, a fitness room, a fee-paying car park, and a first-aid room.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lcsd.gov.hk/clpss/en/webApp/Facility/Details.do?ftid=42&did=11 |title=Aberdeen Tennis and Squash Centre |publisher=Leisure and Cultural Services Department }}</ref>\nUnlike private clubs, the facilities at the Aberdeen Sports Centre and the Aberdeen Tennis and Squash Centre can be reserved by Hong Kong Identity Card holders, locals or foreigners. The price is usually less than HKD $100.\n\nThe Aberdeen Sports Ground is open to the public free of charge whenever the [[Southern District RSA]] football team is not undergoing training.\n\n===Parks===\n[[Image:Aberdeen Promenade Viewing Deck 201508.jpg|left|thumb|Viewing Deck of Aberdeen Promenade]]\n[[Image:\u9999\u6e2f\u4ed4\u4e0a\u6c34\u58581.jpg|left|thumb|Aberdeen Reservoirs]]\n[[Aberdeen Country Park]] (\u9999\u6e2f\u4ed4\u90ca\u91ce\u516c\u5712), commonly known by locals as \"Aberdeen Reservoir Park\" (\u9999\u6e2f\u4ed4\u6c34\u5858\u516c\u5712), is surrounded by the Aberdeen Reservoirs (upper reservoir and lower reservoir). It is a popular spot for local citizens to have barbecue meals as well as a frequent spot for local social organisations and churches to hold group activities. It is also the usual venue of the annual Fall Picnic Day held by primary and secondary schools in the neighborhood.\n\nThe [[Aberdeen Promenade]] (on the Aberdeen side) and the [https://zh.wikipedia.org/zh-hk/%E9%A2%A8%E4%B9%8B%E5%A1%94%E5%85%AC%E5%9C%92 Ap Lei Chau Wind Tower Park] (on the Ap Lei Chau side), located at both sides of the Aberdeen Harbour, are popular spots where local citizens jog and exercise. The two spots are more frequently used between 7 pm and 11 pm, as citizens exercise after work.\n\n[[:zh-yue:\u6df1\u7063\u904a\u8247\u4ff1\u6a02\u90e8|The Aberdeen Marina Club]], located in Wong Chuk Hang (an area inside Aberdeen), provides ice hockey, ice skating, yoga, Tai Chi, swimming, Judo and other experiences for members.\n\n==In popular culture==\nIn 1973, the Hollywood martial arts film ''[[Enter the Dragon]]'', starring [[Bruce Lee]], used Aberdeen Harbour as a filming location for the scenes where the principal characters assemble on Han's junk for the sea journey to his island.\n\nIn 1991, the American action film ''[[Double Impact]]'', starring [[Jean-Claude Van Damme]], includes an escape scene that was shot on the fishing vessels in Aberdeen Harbour, in which Van Damme swims to another fishing vessel in Aberdeen Harbour and ultimately escapes.\n\nIn 1996, the Hong Kong comedy movie ''[[God of Cookery]]'' starred [[Steven Chow]] as the \"Former God of Cookery\" competing with [[Vincent Kok]] as the \"New God of Cookery\" on the Tai Pak floating restaurant, located in the Aberdeen Harbour.\n\nAberdeen Harbour is featured as the first area of the 2001 [[Dreamcast]] video game ''[[Shenmue II]]''. The \"Aberdeen\" depicted in the game differs radically in appearance from its real-life counterpart, being dominated architecturally by low-rise freight storage facilities and colonial-looking neo-historical architecture; this fictional version also faces an urban landscape slightly reminiscent of Hong Kong Island's north shore, an impossible arrangement due to Aberdeen being situated south of this area, behind a mountain range.\n\nIn 2003, the Hollywood movie ''[[Lara Croft Tomb Raider: The Cradle of Life]]'' showed [[Angelina Jolie]] (Lara) in the Aberdeen Harbour on a floating houseboat using the Chinese family's satellite to communicate. This was mirrored to some extent in the 2018 reboot ''[[Tomb_Raider_(film)]]'', where an action scene was filmed in/around the fishing village of Aberdeen Harbour.\n\nIn 2010, the American reality television show ''[[The Amazing Race 17]]'' (Leg 10) featured the Aberdeen Harbour as the location of a Detour task, where competitors searched for the right boat in the dark with a torch. In 2011, the Australian reality television show ''[[The Amazing Race Australia 1]]'' (Leg 3) featured the Jumbo Kingdom floating restaurant as one of the additional tasks' venue, where competitors needed to search for a hidden message inside fortune cookies.\n\nIn the 2012 video game ''[[Sleeping Dogs (video game)|Sleeping Dogs]]'', Aberdeen is featured as one of the districts of Hong Kong that can be explored.\n\nThe Aberdeen Harbour has also appeared in movies such as [[Jackie Chan]]'s ''[[The Protector (1985 film)|The Protector]]'' (1985) and another Hong Kong movie, ''[[Infernal Affairs II]]'' (2003).\n\nAberdeen has occasionally appeared in [[TVB]]'s (a local television station) Food and Travel programs such as [https://zh.wikipedia.org/zh-hk/%E9%A3%9F%E5%BE%97%E5%B3%B0%E9%A8%B7 ''Master So Food''] and [[:zh-tw:\u8857\u574a\u5eda\u795e\u98df\u56db\u65b9|''Neighborhood Gourmet 2'']], as Aberdeen is known throughout Hong Kong for its food culture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://programme.tvb.com/foodandtravel/mastersofood/|title=\u98df\u5f97\u5cf0\u9a37 - \u4e3b\u9801 - tvb.com|website=programme.tvb.com|access-date=3 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170702124456/http://programme.tvb.com/foodandtravel/mastersofood|archive-date=2 July 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://programme.tvb.com/foodandtravel/neighborhoodgourmet/|title=\u8857\u574a\u5eda\u795e - \u4e3b\u9801 - tvb.com|website=programme.tvb.com|access-date=3 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107233010/http://programme.tvb.com/foodandtravel/neighborhoodgourmet|archive-date=7 January 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of harbours in Hong Kong]]\n* [[List of places in Hong Kong]]\n* [[Central Ordnance Munitions Depot]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n* (2005). ''Eyewitness Travel Guides: China'', London: Dorling Kindersley. {{ISBN|1-4053-0876-1}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Aberdeen, Hong Kong}}\n* [http://www.geocities.com/asiaglobe/gallery/aberdeen.htm Aberdeen photo gallery] ([https://web.archive.org/web/20091019185217/http://geocities.com/asiaglobe/gallery/aberdeen.htm Archived] 2009-10-24)\n* [https://maps.google.com/maps?ll=22.245963,114.151769&spn=0.010539,0.014636&t=k&hl=en Satellite view of the site]\n* [https://archive.argent.photos/photo_gallery/aberdeen-wholesale-fish-market/ Rogan Coles Photo Archive - a photo gallery featuring views and activities around the Aberdeen Wholesale Fish Market in Aberdeen, Hong Kong]\n{{Southern District, Hong Kong}}\n{{Ports and harbours of Hong Kong}}\n{{coord|22|14|52|N|114|09|06|E|region:CN-91_type:city(171110)|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Aberdeen, Hong Kong| ]]\n[[Category:Ports and harbours of Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Southern District, Hong Kong]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|Aberdeen, Hong Kong|other uses of Aberdeen|Aberdeen (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use Hong Kong English|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Chinese|title=Aberdeen, Hong Kong|pic=File:Aberdeen Harbour in 2016.jpg|piccap= The view of Aberdeen Harbour from [[Ap Lei Chau Bridge]]|c=\u9999\u6e2f\u4ed4|p=Xi\u0101ngg\u01cengz\u01cei|population=60,000i=h\u0153\u014b<sub>55</sub> k\u0254\u014b<sub>35</sub> ts\u0250\u026a<sub>35</sub>|j=hoeng<sup>1</sup> gong<sup>2</sup> zai<sup>2</sup>|l=Little [[Hong Kong]]|showflag=j}}\n'''Aberdeen''' {{IPAc-en|audio=Aberdeencity.OGG|\u00e6|b|\u0259r|\u02c8|d|i\u02d0|n}} is an area and town on southwest [[Hong Kong Island]] in [[Hong Kong]]. Administratively, it is part of the [[Southern District (Hong Kong)|Southern District]]. While the name \"Aberdeen\" could be taken in a broad sense to encompass the areas of Aberdeen (town), [[Wong Chuk Hang]], [[Ap Lei Chau]], [[Tin Wan]], [[Wah Kwai Estate]] and [[Wah Fu Estate]], it is more often used to refer to the town only. According to the population census conducted in 2011, the total population of the Aberdeen area is approximately 80,000.\n\nAberdeen is famous not only to tourists but also to Hong Kong locals for its [[Aberdeen floating village|floating village]] and floating seafood restaurants located in the Aberdeen Harbour. The [[Tanka (ethnic group)|Tanka people]], who used to live on boats in the Aberdeen Harbour, are generally associated with the fishing industry, and there are still several dozens of them living on boats in the harbour.\n{{TOC limit|2}}\n\n== Etymology ==\nThis town is named in memory of [[George Hamilton-Gordon, 4th Earl of Aberdeen]], former [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] (1852-1855) and former [[Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs]] (1841-1846). The statesman's title was invested to [[Aberdeen]] in Scotland. Hong Kong's \"Aberdeen\" is also the name of a harbour and a housing estate:\n* '''Aberdeen Harbour''' is the harbour between Aberdeen (town) and [[Ap Lei Chau]], and is one of the nine [[List of harbours in Hong Kong|harbours in Hong Kong]]. It is known for its view and is a popular tourist spot. During the fishing moratorium and [[typhoon]] weather, the [[Aberdeen Typhoon Shelters]] have provided a parking spot for [[fishing vessels]] owned by local fishermen.\n* '''Aberdeen Centre''' is a private housing estate located in Aberdeen town, owned by [[Hutchison Whampoa Limited]] company. The twenty buildings (blocks), providing 2,788 private apartments, have provided a home for Hong Kong middle-class families for more than thirty years.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Aberdeen Centre.JPG|thumb|The entrance of the Aberdeen Square in Aberdeen Centre]]\nStarting from the [[Ming Dynasty]], \"Hong Kong\" became the original name for the presently-named Aberdeen village.<ref name=\"Aberdeen Guide\">\"A short guide to Aberdeen\", from a sign at Aberdeen Floating Village, Published by: Southern District Council, Hong Kong. Date visited: 12 October 2009.</ref> In the early 19th century, foreigners who landed near Aberdeen Village mistook the name of the village \"Hong Kong\" for the whole island.  When the foreigners eventually realized their mistake, the name \"Hong Kong\" was already commonly used to refer to the entire island.<ref name=\"Aberdeen Guide\" />\n\nIn Cantonese, Aberdeen is known indigenously as ''Hong Kong Tsai'' which means \"Hong Kong Minor\", \"Son of Hong Kong\" or \"Little Hong Kong\". It is believed that Aberdeen is where the name of Hong Kong (more accurately transcribed as ''Heung Kong'') originates. ''Heung Kong Tsuen'' (\u9999\u6e2f\u6751, \"Hong Kong village\") on Ap Lei Chau was mentioned on [[Ming dynasty|Ming]]-era maps. Another walled village called Heung Kong Wai in Wong Chuk Hang was also founded during the [[Qianlong Emperor|Qianlong]] era of the [[Qing Dynasty]]. ''Hong Kong'' means \"fragrant harbour\", and it was Aberdeen where incense trees (''[[Aquilaria sinensis]]'') from the [[New Territories]] used to be brought for export to other cities in [[China]]. One alternative Chinese name was ''Shek Pai Wan''<ref>[http://irc.aa.tufs.ac.jp/thomson/vol_1/mother/102.html \"Hong Kong\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161027005209/http://irc.aa.tufs.ac.jp/thomson/vol_1/mother/102.html |date=27 October 2016 }}, ''Illustrations of China and Its People'', John Thomson 1837\u20131921, (London, 1873\u20131874)</ref> (\u77f3\u6392\u7063).\n\nIn the [[Second World War]], during the [[Japanese occupation of Hong Kong]] (1941-1945), the Chinese name of Aberdeen, ''Hong Kong Tsai'', was transformed into Japanese as ''Moto Hong Kong'' (\u5143\u9999\u6e2f), meaning \"The Origin of Hong Kong\".\n\n==Authorities==\n[[Image:Aberdeen Municipal Services Building 201508.jpg|right|thumb|Aberdeen Municipal Services Building]]\nThe Aberdeen Kai-Fong Association (abbreviated \"AKA\"; {{zh|t=\u9999\u6e2f\u4ed4\u8857\u574a\u798f\u5229\u6703}}, literally means \"Aberdeen Neighbours Association\"), located at 180B Aberdeen Main Road, provides outreach and elderly services throughout the Southern District. It provides teenager services through the Harmony Life Enrichment Centre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aka.org.hk/hlec/|title=\u5c1a\u8861\u6210\u9577\u53ca\u57f9\u8a13\u4e2d\u5fc3 Harmony Life Enrichment Centre|website=www.aka.org.hk|access-date=18 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140313024251/http://www.aka.org.hk/hlec/|archive-date=13 March 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It also aims to bridge the divide between teenagers and the elderly in the district through the Linkages Centre, located in Carpark Block, Shek Pai Wan Estate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aka.org.hk/index.php|title=Welcome to AKA \u9999\u6e2f\u4ed4\u574a\u6703|website=www.aka.org.hk|access-date=18 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201143757/http://www.aka.org.hk/index.php|archive-date=1 February 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Tung Wah Group of Hospitals]] organisation has a total of four social enterprises in Aberdeen; one of them is Cookeasy,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cookeasy.tungwahcsd.org/aboutus/|title=CookEasy|access-date=20 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017040626/http://cookeasy.tungwahcsd.org/aboutus/|archive-date=17 October 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> which is a project in collaboration with the [[The Hong Kong and China Gas Company|Towngas]] company, creating job opportunities for the disabled and promoting healthy diet culture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tungwah.org.hk/|title=\u6771\u83ef\u4e09\u9662|access-date=20 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130814030037/http://www.tungwah.org.hk/|archive-date=14 August 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAberdeen is one of the 19 constituencies of the [[Southern District Council]]. Each constituency has one elected council member in the [[Southern District Council]]. {{As of|2018}}, the council member representing the area of Aberdeen is Pauline Yam.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.districtcouncils.gov.hk/south/english/members/info/dc_member_list.php|title=Southern District Council - Southern DC Members|website=www.districtcouncils.gov.hk|access-date=3 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180425225045/http://www.districtcouncils.gov.hk/south/english/members/info/dc_member_list.php|archive-date=25 April 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n===Food===\n[[Image:Jumbo Floating Restaurant 1.jpg|left|thumb|Jumbo Floating Restaurant]]\n[[Image:HK Aberdeen \u9999\u6e2f\u4ed4\u820a\u5927\u8857 80 Old Main Street \u5c71\u7abf\u8b1d\u8a18\u9b5a\u86cb Tse Kee Fish Ball Noodle shop sign visitors March-2012.jpg|right|thumb|People queuing up in front of Tse Kee Restaurant]]\n[[Image:Ac4 interior 201508.jpg|right|thumb|Restaurants in Aberdeen Centre]]\n[[Image:BM40615A Lau Kee traditional boat noodles 22-04-2019.jpg|right|thumb|Lau Kee traditional boat noodles]]\nMoored in the harbour between Wong Chuk Hang and [[Ap Lei Chau]], the [[Jumbo Floating Restaurant]] is a popular tourist spot. Designed to resemble a floating palace of imperial China, it has attracted over 30 million visitors since opening in 1976.\n\nThe family-run Shan Loon Tse Kee Fish Balls Restaurant (\u5c71\u7abf\u8b1d\u8a18) served [[Chiuchow cuisine|Chiuchow-style]] [[fish ball]] with soup noodles for 65 years until it closed on 31 March 2012 due to rising fish prices and staffing problems.<ref>Man, Joyce [http://www.cnngo.com/hong-kong/eat/tse-kee-fish-balls-831604 \"Aberdeen's best fish ball shop to close\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229000121/http://www.cnngo.com/hong-kong/eat/tse-kee-fish-balls-831604 |date=29 February 2012 }} ''CNN Go''. 24 February 2012. Retrieved 2012-03-04</ref> The Tse Kee Restaurant served famous guests such as [[Christopher Patten]], former [[Governor of Hong Kong]] (1992-1997); [[Donald Tsang]], former [[Chief Executive of Hong Kong]] (Head of the Government) (2005-2012); [[Henry Tang]], former [[Chief Secretary for Administration of Hong Kong]] (2007-2011); [[Tony Leung Ka-fai|Tony Leung]], a famous actor; [[Chua Lam]], a well-known food critic; and [[Eason Chan]], a celebrated singer. Tse Kee Restaurant helped make \"Aberdeen Fish Balls Noodles Culture\" (\u9999\u6e2f\u4ed4\u9b5a\u86cb\u7c89) well-known.\n\nSix [[Cantonese restaurant|Jau Laus]] (Cantonese restaurants, \u9152\u6a13) such as [[:zh-tw:\u7a3b\u9999\u96c6\u5718|The Tao Heung]] and [[:zh-tw:\u5bcc\u81e8\u96c6\u5718|The Foo Lum]] are located in the neighborhood of Aberdeen. A traditional Cantonese restaurant called Chau Kee (\u5468\u8a18) is located on the Aberdeen Main Road. The noodles restaurants group Nam Kee (\u5357\u8a18) started in Aberdeen in the early 1980s, promoting the \"Aberdeen Fish Balls Noodles Culture\" (\u9999\u6e2f\u4ed4\u9b5a\u86cb\u7c89). The Nam Kee has two restaurants in Aberdeen, along with thirteen others in Hong Kong. There are several other Chinese noodles restaurants located in Aberdeen Centre as well.\n\nFast food restaurants such as [[McDonald's]], [[KFC]], [[Yoshinoya]], [[Fairwood (restaurant)|Fairwood]], [[Caf\u00e9 de Coral (restaurant)|Caf\u00e9 de Coral]] and [[Maxim's Catering|Maxim's MX]] are located in Aberdeen Centre, along with [[Cha Chaan Teng]] (Hong Kong-style fast food restaurants) such as Tai Hing Restaurant (\u592a\u8208) and [[Tsui Wah Restaurant]].\n\nJapanese restaurants such as [[Genki Sushi|Genki]], Watei (\u548c\u4ead) and Sushi Express; Thai One, a Thai restaurant; and Viet's Choice (\u8d8a\u68e7), a Vietnamese restaurant, are also located in Aberdeen Centre. The Pacific Bar is located in Aberdeen Centre as well, serving mainly foreigners living in 'Aberdeen Centre', the private housing estate.\n\n===Festivals and events===\n[[Image:Dragonboat Race in Aberdeen, Hong Kong.jpg|thumb|left|Dragon boat race in Aberdeen Harbour]]\nDuring the [[Tuen Ng Festival]], also known as the Dragon Boat Festival, Aberdeen Harbour becomes the venue of the [[dragon boat]] race in the Southern District. District authorities also hold similar races on Duanwu Festival Day in harbours or rivers of their districts. Although the Aberdeen Harbour race is not as famous as the [[Shing Mun River]] race, it still attracts many tourists and locals every year.\n\nThe Southern District Tourism and Culture Festival,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.travelsouth.hk/en/news/2013|title=Southern District Tourism and Culture Festival 2013|website=www.travelsouth.hk|access-date=20 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203104944/http://www.travelsouth.hk/en/news/2013|archive-date=3 February 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> held by the Southern District Council, organizes races in the Aberdeen Promenade, tours of Aberdeen town, and the Mid-Autumn Fire Dragon Festival in the Aberdeen area every year.\n\nAberdeen Square, located in Aberdeen Centre, is a frequent venue for local organisations' events, including fairs, promotion events and charity events. The square is sometimes used by the [[Southern District Council]] to hold fairs and evening concerts during festivals such as the [[Chinese New Year]] and [[Christmas]].\n\n===Tourism===\n[[File:Aberdeen Sightseeing Sampan Pier 201508.jpg|thumb|right|The view of Sampan Pier near Aberdeen Harbour]]\n[[File:Aberdeen Promenade 201508.jpg|thumb|right|Aberdeen Promenade]]\n\n[[Aberdeen Promenade]], located right next to Aberdeen Harbour on the Aberdeen town side, as well as the [[Ap Lei Chau Bridge]] and [[Aberdeen Channel Bridge]], are famous places for tourists to take photographs of Aberdeen Harbour. The two areas attract many tourists.\n\nThe route of Big Bus Tours Hong Kong<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bigbustours.com/en/hong-kong/hong-kong-bus-tours|title=Hong Kong Bus Tours with Big Bus - Hop-On Discover Hop-Off Explore|website=www.bigbustours.com|access-date=3 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180908215819/https://www.bigbustours.com/en/hong-kong/hong-kong-bus-tours/|archive-date=8 September 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> includes Aberdeen Praya Road, where tourists can take photographs of Aberdeen Harbour on open-top buses.\n\n[[Sampans]] (junks) can be hired by tourists for a tour of Aberdeen Harbour.\n\nAberdeen attracts many tourists as it is in the vicinity of [[Ocean Park Hong Kong|Ocean Park]], also located in the Southern District, near the Aberdeen Sports Ground, which is the other famous theme park apart from [[Hong Kong Disneyland]].\n\n==Infrastructure==\n===Hotels===\nMojo Nomad Aberdeen is located at 100 Shek Pai Wan Road, and has 52 rooms.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mojonomad.com/aberdeen/|title=Aberdeen Harbour Hotel Hong Kong - Co-Living & Co-working|website=Mojo Nomad|access-date=3 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190203071820/https://www.mojonomad.com/aberdeen/|archive-date=3 February 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The L'hotel Island South, at 55 Wong Chuk Hang Road, is located near the popular [[Ocean Park Hong Kong|Ocean Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lhotelgroup.com/en/hotel/lhotel-island-south/Home|title=L'hotel - Family Hotels in Hong Kong - Hong Kong Hotels - L'hotel Island South|website=www.lhotelgroup.com|access-date=3 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181211212652/http://www.lhotelgroup.com/en/hotel/lhotel-island-south/Home|archive-date=11 December 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Hospitals===\n[[Image:HK GranthamHospital.JPG|right|thumb|[[Grantham Hospital]]]]\n[[Grantham Hospital]], located at 125 Wong Chuk Hang Road, has been serving the citizens of the Southern District for more than half a century along with [[Queen Mary Hospital (Hong Kong)|Queen Mary Hospital]] (also located near Aberdeen). Grantham Hospital specializes in comprehensive medical treatment for adult heart and lung diseases, as well as acute geriatrics and palliative medicine services.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ha.org.hk/visitor/ha_visitor_index.asp?Content_ID=100139&Lang=ENG&Dimension=100&Parent_ID=10036&Ver=HTML|title=Grantham Hospital|publisher=Hospital Authority|access-date=18 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201173443/http://www.ha.org.hk/visitor/ha_visitor_index.asp?Content_ID=100139&Lang=ENG&Dimension=100&Parent_ID=10036&Ver=HTML|archive-date=1 February 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n[[File:HK 1 Wong Chuk Hang Road \u9999\u6e2f\u4ed4\u5de5\u696d\u5b78\u6821 Aberdeen Technical School ATS Sir Robert Ho Tung bust April-2012.JPG|thumb|200px]]\n[[Canadian International School of Hong Kong]], Singapore International School and Victoria Shanghai Academy are all located on [[Nam Long Shan]]. Both Canadian International School and Victoria Shanghai Academy are International Baccalaureate World Schools, and run all three educational programs of the IB. The International Montessori School<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ims.edu.hk/|title=Home - The International Montessori School|website=www.ims.edu.hk|access-date=3 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181202023505/https://www.ims.edu.hk/|archive-date=2 December 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> is located on Ap Lei Chau near Aberdeen.\n[[South Island School]] is located nearby on Hong Kong Island.\n\nLocal Chinese high schools in Aberdeen district include Pui Tak Canossian College,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ptcc.edu.hk/|title=\u5609\u8afe\u6492\u57f9\u5fb7\u66f8\u9662|website=www.ptcc.edu.hk|access-date=3 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180626112153/https://www.ptcc.edu.hk/|archive-date=26 June 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> St. Peter's Secondary School in Aberdeen Centre,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stpeter.edu.hk/|title=\u8056\u4f2f\u591a\u797f\u4e2d\u5b78|website=www.stpeter.edu.hk|access-date=3 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181229052958/http://stpeter.edu.hk/|archive-date=29 December 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[:zh:\u9999\u6e2f\u4ed4\u5de5\u696d\u5b78\u6821|Aberdeen Technical School]] in Wong Chuk Hang<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ats.edu.hk/ |title=Aberdeen Technical School |accessdate=2008-04-02 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080331095133/http://www.ats.edu.hk/ |archivedate=2008-03-31 }}</ref> and Aberdeen Baptist Lui Ming Choi College in Ap Lei Chau.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.ablmcc.edu.hk/index/index18.aspx?nnnid=1|title=\u9999\u6e2f\u4ed4\u6d78\u4fe1\u6703\u5442\u660e\u624d\u66f8\u9662|website=web.ablmcc.edu.hk|access-date=3 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190203071820/https://web.ablmcc.edu.hk/index/index18.aspx?nnnid=1|archive-date=3 February 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\n[[File:Aberdeen Promenade Bus Stop.jpg|thumb|\"Aberdeen Promenade, Aberdeen Praya Road\" Bus Stop]]\nTo arrive at Aberdeen or Aberdeen Harbour, travellers can take buses 7, 37A, 37B, 37X, 38, 40P, 41A, 42, 42C, 48, 70, 70A, 71, 71P, 72, 73, 73P, 76, 77, 77X, 78, 91, 91A, 93, 93A, 93C, 94, 94A, 95, 95C, 98, 107, 107P, 170, 973, A10, N72 or N170, and alight at the bus stop \"Aberdeen Promenade, Aberdeen Praya Road\". This bus stop is located directly beside Aberdeen Harbour.\n\nAberdeen is served by [[Pok Fu Lam Road]], [[Aberdeen Tunnel]] and [[Nam Fung Road]] through [[Wong Chuk Hang]]. [[Nam Fung Road]] connects [[Deep Water Bay Road]], which also connects [[Wong Nai Chung Gap Road]] to [[Happy Valley, Hong Kong|Happy Valley]]. A bridge called [[Ap Lei Chau Bridge]] links Aberdeen with [[Ap Lei Chau]] over Aberdeen Harbour.\n\n[[Aberdeen Station (MTR)|Aberdeen Station]], of the proposed [[South Island Line (West)|South Island Line West Section]] of the [[MTR]] will be in Aberdeen. Currently the closest station is [[Wong Chuk Hang Station|Wong Chuk Hang]] on the [[South Island Line]], where feeder bus and minibus routes to Aberdeen are available. \n\nRail passengers may also reach Aberdeen by using [[kai-to]] ferry from [[Ap Lei Chau|Main Street, Ap Lei Chau]] near [[Lei Tung station]] (Exit A1). In addition to the Ap Lei Chau route, regular ferries also depart from Aberdeen to [[Yung Shue Wan]] and [[Sok Kwu Wan]] on [[Lamma Island]], and [[Po Toi Island]].\n\nTransport to and from the boats in the harbour is usually provided by [[sampan]]s. These can also be hired to Lamma Island.\n\n==Recreation==\n===Sports===\n[[Image:Aberdeen Sports Ground viewed from Bennet's Hill.jpg|right|thumb|Aberdeen Sports Ground]]\n[[Aberdeen Sports Ground]] is a major sports and events venue in the [[Southern District (Hong Kong)|Southern District]]. It is usually an annual School Sports Day venue for many local primary and secondary schools in the Southern District.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.lcsd.gov.hk/clpss/en/webApp/Facility/Details.do?ftid=38&did=11 |title=Aberdeen Sports Ground |publisher=Leisure and Cultural Services Department   |df= }}</ref>  It is also the usual venue of the [[Famine events#30 Hour Famine|30-Hour Famine]] held by [[World Vision]] Hong Kong. The Aberdeen Sports Ground is the home ground of the district's football team, [[Southern District RSA]].\n\nThe Aberdeen Sports Centre is located on the 5/F and 6/F of the Aberdeen Municipal Services Building, No. 203 Aberdeen Main Road. The Aberdeen Sports Centre includes a multi-purpose arena, which can be converted into one basketball court or one volleyball court or four badminton courts. There is also a squash court, which can be converted into a table tennis room or a multi-purpose activity room.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lcsd.gov.hk/clpss/en/webApp/Facility/Details.do?ftid=0&did=11 |title=Aberdeen Sports Centre  |publisher=Leisure and Cultural Services Department   |df= }}</ref>\n\nThe Aberdeen Tennis and Squash Centre is located at No. 1 Aberdeen Praya Road, next to the Ocean Court Building. The Aberdeen Tennis and Squash Centre includes 8 tennis courts and six squash courts, which can be converted into table tennis rooms or multi-purpose activity rooms, two American pool rooms, a fitness room, a fee-paying car park, and a first-aid room.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lcsd.gov.hk/clpss/en/webApp/Facility/Details.do?ftid=42&did=11 |title=Aberdeen Tennis and Squash Centre |publisher=Leisure and Cultural Services Department }}</ref>\nUnlike private clubs, the facilities at the Aberdeen Sports Centre and the Aberdeen Tennis and Squash Centre can be reserved by Hong Kong Identity Card holders, locals or foreigners. The price is usually less than HKD $100.\n\nThe Aberdeen Sports Ground is open to the public free of charge whenever the [[Southern District RSA]] football team is not undergoing training.\n\n===Parks===\n[[Image:Aberdeen Promenade Viewing Deck 201508.jpg|left|thumb|Viewing Deck of Aberdeen Promenade]]\n[[Image:\u9999\u6e2f\u4ed4\u4e0a\u6c34\u58581.jpg|left|thumb|Aberdeen Reservoirs]]\n[[Aberdeen Country Park]] (\u9999\u6e2f\u4ed4\u90ca\u91ce\u516c\u5712), commonly known by locals as \"Aberdeen Reservoir Park\" (\u9999\u6e2f\u4ed4\u6c34\u5858\u516c\u5712), is surrounded by the Aberdeen Reservoirs (upper reservoir and lower reservoir). It is a popular spot for local citizens to have barbecue meals as well as a frequent spot for local social organisations and churches to hold group activities. It is also the usual venue of the annual Fall Picnic Day held by primary and secondary schools in the neighborhood.\n\nThe [[Aberdeen Promenade]] (on the Aberdeen side) and the [https://zh.wikipedia.org/zh-hk/%E9%A2%A8%E4%B9%8B%E5%A1%94%E5%85%AC%E5%9C%92 Ap Lei Chau Wind Tower Park] (on the Ap Lei Chau side), located at both sides of the Aberdeen Harbour, are popular spots where local citizens jog and exercise. The two spots are more frequently used between 7 pm and 11 pm, as citizens exercise after work.\n\n[[:zh-yue:\u6df1\u7063\u904a\u8247\u4ff1\u6a02\u90e8|The Aberdeen Marina Club]], located in Wong Chuk Hang (an area inside Aberdeen), provides ice hockey, ice skating, yoga, Tai Chi, swimming, Judo and other experiences for members.\n\n==In popular culture==\nIn 1973, the Hollywood martial arts film ''[[Enter the Dragon]]'', starring [[Bruce Lee]], used Aberdeen Harbour as a filming location for the scenes where the principal characters assemble on Han's junk for the sea journey to his island.\n\nIn 1991, the American action film ''[[Double Impact]]'', starring [[Jean-Claude Van Damme]], includes an escape scene that was shot on the fishing vessels in Aberdeen Harbour, in which Van Damme swims to another fishing vessel in Aberdeen Harbour and ultimately escapes.\n\nIn 1996, the Hong Kong comedy movie ''[[God of Cookery]]'' starred [[Steven Chow]] as the \"Former God of Cookery\" competing with [[Vincent Kok]] as the \"New God of Cookery\" on the Tai Pak floating restaurant, located in the Aberdeen Harbour.\n\nAberdeen Harbour is featured as the first area of the 2001 [[Dreamcast]] video game ''[[Shenmue II]]''. The \"Aberdeen\" depicted in the game differs radically in appearance from its real-life counterpart, being dominated architecturally by low-rise freight storage facilities and colonial-looking neo-historical architecture; this fictional version also faces an urban landscape slightly reminiscent of Hong Kong Island's north shore, an impossible arrangement due to Aberdeen being situated south of this area, behind a mountain range.\n\nIn 2003, the Hollywood movie ''[[Lara Croft Tomb Raider: The Cradle of Life]]'' showed [[Angelina Jolie]] (Lara) in the Aberdeen Harbour on a floating houseboat using the Chinese family's satellite to communicate. This was mirrored to some extent in the 2018 reboot ''[[Tomb_Raider_(film)]]'', where an action scene was filmed in/around the fishing village of Aberdeen Harbour.\n\nIn 2010, the American reality television show ''[[The Amazing Race 17]]'' (Leg 10) featured the Aberdeen Harbour as the location of a Detour task, where competitors searched for the right boat in the dark with a torch. In 2011, the Australian reality television show ''[[The Amazing Race Australia 1]]'' (Leg 3) featured the Jumbo Kingdom floating restaurant as one of the additional tasks' venue, where competitors needed to search for a hidden message inside fortune cookies.\n\nIn the 2012 video game ''[[Sleeping Dogs (video game)|Sleeping Dogs]]'', Aberdeen is featured as one of the districts of Hong Kong that can be explored.\n\nThe Aberdeen Harbour has also appeared in movies such as [[Jackie Chan]]'s ''[[The Protector (1985 film)|The Protector]]'' (1985) and another Hong Kong movie, ''[[Infernal Affairs II]]'' (2003).\n\nAberdeen has occasionally appeared in [[TVB]]'s (a local television station) Food and Travel programs such as [https://zh.wikipedia.org/zh-hk/%E9%A3%9F%E5%BE%97%E5%B3%B0%E9%A8%B7 ''Master So Food''] and [[:zh-tw:\u8857\u574a\u5eda\u795e\u98df\u56db\u65b9|''Neighborhood Gourmet 2'']], as Aberdeen is known throughout Hong Kong for its food culture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://programme.tvb.com/foodandtravel/mastersofood/|title=\u98df\u5f97\u5cf0\u9a37 - \u4e3b\u9801 - tvb.com|website=programme.tvb.com|access-date=3 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170702124456/http://programme.tvb.com/foodandtravel/mastersofood|archive-date=2 July 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://programme.tvb.com/foodandtravel/neighborhoodgourmet/|title=\u8857\u574a\u5eda\u795e - \u4e3b\u9801 - tvb.com|website=programme.tvb.com|access-date=3 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107233010/http://programme.tvb.com/foodandtravel/neighborhoodgourmet|archive-date=7 January 2019|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of harbours in Hong Kong]]\n* [[List of places in Hong Kong]]\n* [[Central Ordnance Munitions Depot]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n* (2005). ''Eyewitness Travel Guides: China'', London: Dorling Kindersley. {{ISBN|1-4053-0876-1}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Aberdeen, Hong Kong}}\n* [http://www.geocities.com/asiaglobe/gallery/aberdeen.htm Aberdeen photo gallery] ([https://web.archive.org/web/20091019185217/http://geocities.com/asiaglobe/gallery/aberdeen.htm Archived] 2009-10-24)\n* [https://maps.google.com/maps?ll=22.245963,114.151769&spn=0.010539,0.014636&t=k&hl=en Satellite view of the site]\n{{Southern District, Hong Kong}}\n{{Ports and harbours of Hong Kong}}\n{{coord|22|14|52|N|114|09|06|E|region:CN-91_type:city(171110)|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Aberdeen, Hong Kong| ]]\n[[Category:Ports and harbours of Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Southern District, Hong Kong]]\n", "name_user": "Tingyat", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added an external link to a photo gallery featuring views and activities around the Aberdeen Wholesale Fish Market in Aberdeen, Hong Kong"